EDA of In-Patient Data for Fraud-detection and Feature engineering¶

Introduction¶

The given dataset contains information on the provider, disease group, referral region and charges and payments for 163,065 hospital-disease group combinations. Based on the paper readings done so far, healthcare fraud can be detected by considering the appropriate unit of analysis and aggregating statistics and ratios across 20 different combinatorial levels. In prior work, we explored the data available to understand possible patterns and to create new features. Here, we extend the analysis, create new features and attempt to cluster the observations.

Feature Engineering¶

Based on prior explorations, we calculated the following ratios:

  • Medicare payments to Total Payments
  • Medicare payments to covered charges
  • Total payments to covered charges
  • Medicare payment/discharge
  • Total payment/discharge
  • Covered charges/discharge
In [4]:
#Adding additional data columns to enable factor engineering

data['medicare_by_total'] = (data['average_medicare_payments'] / data['average_total_payments'])
data['medicare_by_covered'] = (data['average_medicare_payments'] / data['average_covered_charges'])
data['total_by_covered'] = (data['average_total_payments'] / data['average_covered_charges'])
data['medicare_per_discharge'] = (data['average_medicare_payments'] / data['total_discharges'])
data['total_per_discharge'] = (data['average_total_payments'] / data['total_discharges'])
data['covered_per_discharge'] = (data['average_covered_charges'] / data['total_discharges'])

plt.figure(figsize = (10,6))

Out[5]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Histogram of ratio of medicare payments to covered charges')

The ratio of medicare payments to covered charges for a majority of observations fall between 0 and 1. However, a non-zero number of observations have a ratio of average medicare payment to covered charges above 1, and some above 2 as well. Prima facie, this seems suspicious and is worth exploring further. This ratio can therefore serve as an important feature in clustering the observations.

Ideally, average medicare payments must be lower than or equal to average coverage. This would mean on a scatterplot, they would be on or below the diagonal. However, as can be seen from this graph, the observations are widely distributed. However, the count of observation with atypical values are very low as seen from the histogram!This hints at these two variables and their ratio being useful features.

Further we calculated the following summary statistics:

  • Median
  • Standard Deviation

Across the following groupings:

  • Provider, state and disease group
  • disease group by state, disease group by referral group

data = pd.merge(data, data_drg_state_stat2, left_on = ['DRG_def', 'provider_state'], right_on = ['DRG_def', 'provider_state'])

#level 1 - drg X referral group

data = pd.merge(data, data_drg_rfg_stat2, left_on = ['DRG_def', 'hospital_referral_region'], right_on = ['DRG_def', 'hospital_referral_region'])

Using the summary statistics we have calculated so far, for each observation we created a measure of deviation defined as the number of standard deviations above/below the mean.

In [10]:
#Creating deviation measures ( abs(value - mean)/std deviation)
#deviation measure for provider mean and drg and state median
data['dev_provider_cc'] = (data['average_covered_charges'] - data['median_provider_cc'])/data['sd_provider_cc']
data['dev_provider_tp'] = (data['average_total_payments'] - data['median_provider_tp'])/data['sd_provider_tp']
data['dev_provider_mp'] = (data['average_medicare_payments'] - data['median_provider_mp'])/data['sd_provider_mp']
data['dev_provider_td'] = (data['total_discharges'] - data['median_provider_td'])/data['sd_provider_td'] 
data['dev_provider_tpd']= (data['total_per_discharge'] - data['median_provider_tpd']) / data['sd_provider_tpd'] 

data['dev_drg_cc'] = (data['average_covered_charges'] - data['median_drg_cc'])/data['sd_drg_cc']
data['dev_drg_tp'] = (data['average_total_payments'] - data['median_drg_tp'])/data['sd_drg_tp']
data['dev_drg_mp'] = (data['average_medicare_payments'] - data['median_drg_mp'])/data['sd_drg_mp']
data['dev_drg_td'] = (data['total_discharges'] - data['median_drg_td'])/data['sd_drg_td'] 
data['dev_drg_tpd']= (data['total_per_discharge'] - data['median_drg_tpd']) / data['sd_drg_tpd'] 

data['dev_state_cc'] = (data['average_covered_charges'] - data['median_state_cc'])/data['sd_state_cc']
data['dev_state_tp'] = (data['average_total_payments'] - data['median_state_tp'])/data['sd_state_tp']
data['dev_state_mp'] = (data['average_medicare_payments'] - data['median_state_mp'])/data['sd_state_mp']
data['dev_state_cc'] = (data['total_discharges'] - data['median_state_td'])/data['sd_state_td'] 
data['dev_state_tpd']= (data['total_per_discharge'] - data['median_state_tpd']) / data['sd_state_tpd'] 

#deviation measure for drg and state
data['dev_drg_state_cc'] = (data['average_covered_charges'] - data['median_drg_state_cc'] )/data['sd_drg_state_cc']
data['dev_drg_state_tp'] = (data['average_total_payments'] - data['median_drg_state_tp'])/data['sd_drg_state_tp']
data['dev_drg_state_mp'] = (data['average_medicare_payments'] - data['median_drg_state_mp'])/data['sd_drg_state_mp']
data['dev_drg_state_td'] = (data['total_discharges'] - data['median_drg_state_td'])/data['sd_drg_state_td'] 
data['dev_drg_state_tpd']= (data['total_per_discharge'] - data['median_drg_state_tpd']) / data['sd_drg_state_tpd'] 

#deviation measure for drg and hospital referral group
data['dev_drg_rfg_cc'] = (data['average_covered_charges'] - data['median_drg_rfg_cc']) / data['sd_drg_rfg_cc']
data['dev_drg_rfg_tp'] = (data['average_total_payments'] - data['median_drg_rfg_tp'])/data['sd_drg_rfg_tp']
data['dev_drg_rfg_mp'] = (data['average_medicare_payments'] - data['median_drg_rfg_mp'])/data['sd_drg_rfg_mp']
data['dev_drg_rfg_td'] = (data['total_discharges'] - data['median_drg_rfg_td'])/data['sd_drg_rfg_td'] 
data['dev_drg_rfg_tpd']= (data['total_per_discharge'] - data['median_drg_rfg_tpd']) / data['sd_drg_rfg_tpd']

With these new features we have a measure of the number of standard deviations from the mean for:

  • Covered charges
  • Total Payments
  • Medicare Payments
  • Total Discharges
  • Total payment per discharge

For each of these, we have deviations from mean at the level of :

  • Provider
  • Disease Group
  • State
  • Disease group by each state
  • Disease group by each hospital referral region

Further Future Analysis: Clustering Observations based on available data¶

As a final exercise, we will attempt to cluster these observations on the basis of the available data. This serves two purposes:

  1. Reducing the number of observations which need to be examined manually
  2. Provide a model for identifying fraudulent transaction as they happen

#Cleanin up data for modelling by removing factors and null values
drop_vars = data.iloc[:, 18:68].columns.tolist()

null_col = null_col[ null_col > 0]
#Looping through to replace NAs with mean values
null_col = null_col.index
for col in null_col:
  data.loc[:, col].fillna(data.loc[:, col].mean(), inplace = True)

#Loading required packages
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

To enable easier modelling with K-means, we use one-hot encoding for Disease groups, referral regions, states and providers. To be able to create the model without overloading our system, we limit levels to 26 for each of these variables

In [13]:
#Recategorizing variables to enable one hot encoding
drg_levels = data['DRG_def'].value_counts().nlargest(25).index.tolist()
data['new_drg'] = data['DRG_def'].apply(lambda x: x if x in drg_levels else 'other')
hrr_levels = data['hospital_referral_region'].value_counts(normalize = True).nlargest(25).index.tolist()
data['new_hrr'] = data['hospital_referral_region'].apply(lambda x: x if x in hrr_levels else 'other')
state_levels = data['provider_state'].value_counts(normalize = True).nlargest(25).index.tolist()
data['new_state'] = data['provider_state'].apply(lambda x: x if x in state_levels else 'other')
pid_levels = data['provider_id'].value_counts(normalize = True).nlargest(25).index.tolist()
data['new_pid'] = data['provider_id'].apply(lambda x: x if x in pid_levels else 'other')

#Preparing the model
#Identifying best set of clusters
sse = []

for n in range(2,11):
  kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = n, random_state= 257)
  kmeans.fit(data_model)
  sse.append(kmeans.inertia_)

In order to identify the ideal number of clusters, we tested clusters from 2 to 11. We then drew an elbow plot to identify the best option. Based on the lowest SSE plot, 6 clusters seems to be the best option.

Based on the saliency of the clusters, Cluster 4 and 2 seem to be a good fits for our purposes. As seen above, they includes a fairly low number of observations: 4% and 1% of the data. As seen in the table above, cluster 0 also has abnormally high median values for medicare payments, covered charges and total payments.

Interestingly, Groups 0 and 2 show some possible trends in the deviation measures. With more granular data we could probably cluster such that we have smaller, more numerous clusters with more than one being possible fraudulent. As can be seen in the table below, Group 4 only has representations from 33 disease groups, while group 2 and 0 have almost all disease groups represented.

Principal Component Analysis¶

We use a 2 component PCA to visually estimate how divergent the different clusters are.

In [30]:
#Attempting PCA analysis 
x = data_model.copy()
y = kmm.labels_
In [31]:
from sklearn. decomposition import PCA
pca = PCA(n_components = 2)

principalComponents = pca.fit_transform(x)
principalDf = pd.DataFrame(data = principalComponents
             , columns = ['principal component 1', 'principal component 2'])
finalDf = pd.concat([principalDf, data_check['label']], axis = 1)
In [32]:
plt.figure(figsize = (15,15))
sns.color_palette('tab10')
sns.scatterplot(x = 'principal component 1', y = 'principal component 2', hue = 'label', data = finalDf, palette='tab10')
plt.title("2 component PCA for new clusters", loc = 'center')
Out[32]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, '2 component PCA for new clusters')

As expected cluster 4 is significantly different from clusters 0,1, 2, 3 and 5. Clusters 4 and 0 are the closest, which explains our earlier thought that some observations in cluster 0 would be better fit in cluster 4. However cluster 2 is completely hidden behind cluster 3, indicating they are similar however, the difference could be between fraudulent and non-fraudulent observations.
